'''Glen Anthony Rice, Jr.''' (born January 1, 1991) is an American professional [[basketball]] [[shooting guard]] with the [[Washington Wizards]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He was drafted by the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] in the [[2013 NBA Draft]], but he was traded on draft night to the Wizards. He formerly played [[college basketball]] for the [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets men's basketball|Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets basketball team]] but was dismissed from the team during his junior season for the [[2011<U+2013>12 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets men's basketball team|2011<U+2013>12 Yellow Jackets team]] and went pro the following season, playing a year for the [[Rio Grande Valley Vipers]] of the [[NBA Development League]]. He is the son of NBA [[NBA All-Star Game|All-Star]] [[Glen Rice]].

In high school, Rice was the [[Cobb County, Georgia]] player of the year as a junior at [[George Walton Comprehensive High School]] and an All-State selection as both a junior and senior. He joined a highly recruited class at Georgia Tech. He was among the statistical leaders in numerous categories within the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC) during his playing time.

==High school==
As a junior, Rice was the 2008 Cobb County [[high school basketball]] boy's player of the year, according to the ''[[Marietta Daily Journal]]'', as well as a third team (honorable mention) All-State selection by ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdjonline.com/pages/full_story/push?article-Talent+level+no+less+as+new+season+tips+off%20&id=4904649|title=Talent level no less as new season tips off|accessdate=2011-11-26|date=2009-11-26|work=[[Marietta Daily Journal]]|author=Hores, Emily}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/blogs/content/shared-blogs/ajc/prepsports/entries/2008/03/28/ajc_2008_boys_allstate_basketball.html|title=AJC 2008 Boys All-State Georgia High School Basketball Team|accessdate=2011-11-26|date=2008-03-28|work=[[The Palm Beach Post]]|author=Hores, Emily}}</ref><ref name=MUSBLoI>{{cite web|url=http://www.ramblinwreck.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/111308aaj.html|title=Mfon Udofia Signs Basketball Letter-of-Intent: Nation's 30th-ranked senior becomes fourth Yellow Jacket signee|accessdate=2011-11-26|date=2008-11-19|work=RamblinWreck.com}}</ref> When he signed his [[National Letter of Intent]] in November 2008, Rice was described as a late bloomer.<ref name=MUSBLoI/> As a senior, he was a Class AAAAA All-state selection (2nd team by ''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' and 1st team by the Georgia Sportswriters Association).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/hotjobs/content/sports/highschool/stories/2009/03/27/georgia_all_state_basketball.html|title=All-State basketball teams for 2008-2009|accessdate=2011-11-26|date=2009-03-27|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gainesvilletimes.com/archives/16621/|title=Basketball: Lady Wolves dominate All-State team|accessdate=2011-11-26|date=2009-03-26|work=[[The Gainesville Times (Georgia)|Gainesville Times]]}}</ref>  

Rice was ranked as the 13th, 32nd and 35th best [[high school basketball]] shooting guard in the country as a senior in 2009 by [[Rivals.com]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rivals.yahoo.com/basketballrecruiting/basketball/recruiting/player-Glen-Rice-64264;_ylt=AhsdnYbabw7J.mZGgJQI9rvSO5B4|title=Glen Rice|accessdate=2011-11-25|publisher=[[Rivals.com]]}}</ref> [[Scout.com]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scouthoops.scout.com/a.z?s=75&p=8&c=1&nid=3499097|title=Glen Rice|accessdate=2011-11-25|publisher=[[Scout.com]]}}</ref> and [[ESPN]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/basketball/recruiting/player/_/id/42834/glen-rice-jr|title=Glen Rice, Jr.|accessdate=2011-11-25|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> respectively. His father's alma mater, [[University of Michigan]] did not recruit him for [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|their basketball team]] until after he had already committed to Georgia Tech.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/glen-rice-jr-and-tim-hardaway-jr-might-meet-again-in-atlantic-city/|title=Georgia Tech's Glen Rice Jr. and Michigan's Tim Hardaway Jr. reunited in Atlantic City|accessdate=2011-11-25|date=2010-11-27|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Rothstein, Michael}}</ref> Rice, Jr. was part of a Georgia Tech recruiting class that was ranked 21st in the nation and included [[Derrick Favors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/news/story?id=3833558|title=Favors to stay home, play at Ga. Tech|accessdate=2011-11-26|date=2009-01-15|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> 

Rice's Georgia Tech biography credits him with leading his high school to a state title in basketball as a senior,<ref name=4GRJ>{{cite web|url=http://www.ramblinwreck.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/ricejr_glen00.html|title=41 Glen Rice, Jr.|accessdate=2011-11-26|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=RamblinWreck.com}}</ref> but the [[Georgia High School Association]] records show that his high school did not win a state championship in any sport during his senior season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghsa.net/files/documents/Constitution/GHSA_RR_2008-2009.pdf|title=Results & Records of State Playoff Events 2008-09|accessdate=2011-11-26|publisher=[[Georgia High School Association]]}}</ref>  ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' confirms that his basketball team was eliminated in the second round of the class AAAAA tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=126E852586BD5F50&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Football departures, women's hoops, Derrick Favors|date=2009-03-06|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|quote=The high school careers of Glen Rice (Walton) and Kammeon Holsey (Hancock Central) ended in the second round, with Rice scoring 14 in a narrow loss to ...}}</ref>
