==College==
Rice started his freshman season on the bench,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://admin.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/the-blessings-and-burdens-of-being-the-son-of-an-nba-player-in-college-basketball/|title=Blessings and burdens part of being the son of an NBA player in the college basketball world|accessdate=2011-11-25|date=2010-11-25|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Rothstein, Michael}}</ref> but he played in all but one game for the [[2009-10 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets men's basketball team]]. He scored in double figures six times, including the [[2010 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]] second round game against [[2009-10 Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball team|Ohio State]].<ref name=GRJGS10>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/player/gamelog/_/id/45525/year/2010/glen-rice-jr|title=Glen Rice Jr. Game-by-Game Stats (2009-10)|accessdate=2011-11-26|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> He had season highs for [[point (basketball)|points]] (17), [[rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] (8) and [[assist (basketball)|assists]] (4) in the March 2, 2010 game against [[2009-10 Clemson Tigers men's basketball team|Clemson]].<ref name=GRJGS10/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=300610228|title=Georgia Tech 80 (19-10, 7-8 ACC): Clemson 91 (21-8, 9-6 ACC)|accessdate=2011-11-26|date=2010-03-02|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> He started the final 11 games of his freshman season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/sixers/features/130626-glen-rice-jr-spotlight|title=Spotlight: Glen Rice, Jr.|accessdate=2013-06-28|date=|publisher=[[NBA.com]]}}</ref> Rice earned ACC All-Academic team recognition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theacc.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/030310aab.html|title=2010 ACC All-Academic Men's Basketball Team Announced: A pair of three-time All-Academic team selections headline the 2010 All-Atlantic Coast Conference Academic Men's Basketball Team.|accessdate=2011-11-26|date=2010-03-03|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> Although he was one of four people to receive at least one first place vote for ACC Rookie of the year,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theacc.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/030910aab.html|title=Jackets' Favors Named ACC Rookie of the Year: Freshman forward becomes 11th Georgia Tech player to be honored.|accessdate=2011-12-02|date=2010-03-09|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=TheACC.com}}</ref> he was not on the five-player ACC All-Rookie team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theacc.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/030810aac.html|title=Atlantic Coast Sports Media Association Announces 2009-10 All-ACC Teams: Top three scorers Vasquez, Scheyer and Delaney named unanimous first-team picks.|accessdate=2011-12-02|date=2010-03-08|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=TheACC.com}}</ref>

As a sophomore, Rice posted six 20-point games,<ref name=GRJsf3g/> but three times (all Georgia Tech victories) he played at least 10 minutes while scoring no points.<ref name=GRJGS11/> He started 23 of 31 games that year.<ref name=RJlGTpS7/> Rice ranked second on the team in terms of minutes, points, rebounds, assists and [[steal (basketball)|steals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/team/stats/_/id/59/year/2011/georgia-tech-yellow-jackets|title=Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets Stats - 2010-11|accessdate=2011-11-26|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> He ranked 17th in the ACC in scoring and 6th in steals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theacc.com/sports/m-baskbl/stats/2010-2011/confldrs.html#conf.wki|title=2010-11 ACC Basketball Statistics|accessdate=2011-11-26|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> Three times Rice had more than 10 rebounds, giving him three [[double-doubles]].<ref name=GRJGS11>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/player/gamelog/_/id/45525/year/2011/glen-rice-jr|title=Glen Rice Jr. Game-by-Game Stats (2010-11)|accessdate=2011-11-26|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Early in his sophomore season, the {{cbb link|2010|sex=men|team=Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets|school=Georgia Institute of Technology|title=2010&ndash;11 Yellow Jackets team}} was in the same Legends Classic Tournament as the [[2010-11 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team]], but since the Wolverines did not qualify for the championship game, he did not get to play against his father's alma mater.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ww.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/michigan-forward-jordan-morgan-excels-again-and-glen-rices-dream-matchup/|title=Michigan forward Jordan Morgan excels again and Glen Rice's dream matchup fizzles|accessdate=2011-11-25|date=2010-11-26|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Rothstein, Michael}}</ref> In mid January, Rice had his first back-to-back twenty-point scoring nights on January 16 and January 19 against [[2010<U+2013>11 North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball team|North Carolina]] and [[2010<U+2013>11 Wake Forest Demon Deacons men's basketball team|Wake Forest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=310160059|title=North Carolina 58 (12-5, 2-1 ACC); Georgia Tech 78 (8-8, 1-2 ACC)|accessdate=2011-12-02|date=2011-01-16|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=310190059|title=Wake Forest 39 (7-12, 0-4 ACC); Georgia Tech 74 (9-8, 2-2 ACC)|accessdate=2011-12-02|date=2011-01-19|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Later in the season, he posted season highs in rebounds and point in back-to-back games:<ref name=GRJGS11/> Rice had 12 rebounds on January 30 against the [[2010<U+2013>11 Maryland Terrapins men's basketball team|Maryland Terrapins]] and 28 points on February 3 against the {{cbb link|2010|sex=men|team=Miami Hurricanes|school=University of Miami|title=Miami Hurricanes}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=310300059|title=Maryland 74 (14-7, 4-3 ACC); Georgia Tech 63 (10-10, 3-4 ACC)|accessdate=2011-11-26|date=2011-01-30|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=310342390|title=Georgia Tech 57 (10-11, 3-5 ACC); Miami (FL) 59 (13-9, 2-6 ACC)|accessdate=2011-11-26|date=2011-02-03|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Coach [[Paul Hewitt]] suspended him for the final three games of the season.<ref name=GRJkot>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/7680883/georgia-tech-yellow-jackets-glen-rice-jr-kicked-team-shooting|title=Glen Rice Jr. kicked off team|accessdate=2012-03-14|date=2012-03-13|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>

Following the [[2011 NBA Draft]] selection of [[Iman Shumpert]], Rice was the leading returning scorer for the 2011&ndash;12 Yellow Jackets. He was suspended for the first three games of the [[2011<U+2013>12 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2011<U+2013>12 season]] for an undisclosed violation of team rules.<ref name=GRJsf3g>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/7221853/glen-rice-jr-georgia-tech-yellow-jackets-sit-1st-three-games|title=Glen Rice Jr. suspended for 3 games|accessdate=2011-11-25|date=2011-11-11|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://aol.sportingnews.com/ncaa-basketball/story/2011-11-12/georgia-tech-suspends-glen-rice-jr-for-three-games|title=Georgia Tech suspends Glen Rice Jr. for three games|accessdate=2011-11-25|date=2011-11-12|publisher=[[Sporting News]]}}</ref> When he returned to the lineup following his suspension on November 18, he assumed the role of a [[sixth man]].<ref name=RJlGTpS7>{{cite web|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/AP7c6a2382671d410eb3002a4711755d2e.html|title=Rice Jr. leads Georgia Tech past Siena 72-44|accessdate=2011-11-25|date=2011-11-23|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref> In his return to the starting lineup on December 3 against the {{cbb link|2011|sex=men|team=Tulane Green Wave|school=Tulane University|title=Tulane Green Wave}}, Rice not only posted his first double-double of the season with 11 points and 11 rebounds, but also had his first career 4-[[blocked shot]] effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=313372655|title=Georgia Tech 52 (4-4, 0-1 away); Tulane 57 (9-0, 7-0 home)|accessdate=2011-12-07|date=2011-12-03|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> He posted his second double-double of the season on December 19 against {{cbb link|2011|sex=men|team=Alabama A&M Bulldogs|school=Alabama A&M|title=Alabama A&M}} when he tallied 21 points, 10 rebounds and 3 blocks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=313530059|title=Alabama A&M 54 (2-4, 0-4 away); Georgia Tech 65 (6-4, 3-0 home)|accessdate=2011-12-20|date=2011-12-19|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Rice followed that with a double-double in his next outing on December 22 against [[2011<U+2013>12 Mercer Bears men's basketball team|Mercer]] when he posted 19 points and 11 rebounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=313560059|title=Mercer 65 (8-5, 1-1 A-Sun); Georgia Tech 59 (7-5, 4-1 home)|accessdate=2011-12-23|date=2011-12-22|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> The ACC requires that a player play in 75% of his team's games to be qualified for statistical rankings. After his 9th game on December 22, Rice qualified despite the three game suspension and is now ranked among the conference leaders in points, rebounds, blocks and steals per game  plus [[field goal percentage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theacc.com/sports/m-baskbl/stats/2011-2012/confldrs.html#conf.wki|title=2011-12 ACC Basketball: Overall Statistics|accessdate=2011-12-23|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=TheACC.com}}</ref> On December 29, Rice had a scoreless night during a loss to [[2011<U+2013>12 Fordham Rams men's basketball team|Fordham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=313632230|title=Georgia Tech 66 (7-6, 2-2 away); Fordham 72 (6-6, 5-1 home)|accessdate=2011-12-31|date=2011-12-29|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> On January 7 against #3 [[2011<U+2013>12 Duke Blue Devils men's basketball team|Duke]], he posted a career-high-tying 28 points with 8 rebounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=320070059|title=Ryan Kelly, Seth Curry pace Blue Devils to victory over Yellow Jackets|accessdate=2012-01-08|date=2012-01-07|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> On January 11, against [[2011<U+2013>12 NC State Wolfpack men's basketball team|NC State]], he had 22 points to mark his second career back-to-back 20-point performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=320110152|title=Georgia Tech 82, NC State 71|accessdate=2012-01-12|date=2012-01-11|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> On January 29, Rice was hobbled with a big toe injury that limited him to 4 points in 22 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/colleges/hobbled-rice-struggles-for-yellow-jackets-as-woes-continue-with-93-81-loss-at-no-7-tar-heels/2012/01/29/gIQArY3DbQ_story.html|title=Hobbled Rice struggles for Yellow Jackets as woes continue with 93-81 loss at No. 7 Tar Heels|accessdate=2012-02-02|date=2012-01-29|work=[[The Washington Post]]}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> At the beginning of February, Rice was sidelined with a foot injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/02/sports/ncaabasketball/ncaa-basketball-roundup.html|title=Georgetown Shuts Down Slumping Connecticut|accessdate=2012-02-02|date=2012-02-01|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> He returned to the lineup for three games before being suspended indefinitely for non-basketball issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/college/mensbasketball/acc/story/2012-02-17/georgia-tech-rice-suspended/53137608/1|title=Georgia Tech suspends guard Glen Rice Jr. indefinitely|accessdate=2012-02-18|date=2012-02-17|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref><ref name=TGRJsi/> The suspension was Rice's second of the season and third in his college career.<ref name=TGRJsi>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/georgia-tech/techs-glen-rice-jr-1353258.html|title=Tech's Glen Rice Jr. suspended indefinitely|accessdate=2012-02-18|date=2012-02-17|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|author=Sugiura, Ken}}</ref> Coach [[Brian Gregory]] dismissed him from the team on March 13 following an incident involving [[driving under the influence]] and discharging a firearm while under the influence in which Rice was charged with permitting unlawful operation.<ref name=GRJkot/> Following the bad publicity [[Bo Ryan]] received about blocking a transfer, Gregory stated that he would not block a transfer to any university.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collegebasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2012/05/02/brian-gregory-learns-from-bo-ryan-will-not-restrict-glen-rice-jr-transfer/|title=Brian Gregory learns from Bo Ryan, will not restrict Glen Rice Jr. transfer|accessdate=2012-07-10|date=2012-05-02|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|author=Martin, Daniel}}</ref> Following his dismissal, [[CBS Sports]] regarded him as one of the top 20 potential transfers in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/collegebasketball/recruiting/blog/eye-on-college-basketball-recruiting/19135265/recruiting-mailbag-how-does-kentucky-look-for-2013|title=Recruiting mailbag: How does Kentucky look for 2013?|accessdate=2012-06-09|date=2012-05-23|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]|author=Borzello, Jeff}}</ref>

==Pro career==
===Rio Grande Valley Vipers===
Rice was drafted in the fourth round of the November 2, 2012 [[NBA Development League]] draft by the [[Rio Grande Valley Vipers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/dleague/riograndevalley/VipersNBADLDraft2012.html|title=Vipers select Johnson in first round of NBADL Draft|accessdate=2012-11-21|date=2012-11-02|publisher=[[NBA.com]]}}</ref> He made the opening day roster and made his professional debut on November 23 against the Bakersfield Jam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/sports/local/article_90d022f8-3533-11e2-8d29-0019bb30f31a.html|title=RGV Capsules: Nurse adjusts as Vipers begin season|accessdate=2012-12-01|date=2012-11-22|work=[[Brownsville Herald]]|author=Hinojosa, David}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/dleague/games/20121123/BAKRGV/gameinfo.html#nbaGIboxscore|title=Friday, November 23, 2012: 8:00 PM ET - State Farm Arena, Hidalgo, TX|accessdate=2012-12-01|date=2012-11-23|publisher=[[NBA.com]]}}</ref> Rice did not play much early in the year, totalling only 147 minutes in the first 22 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.draftexpress.com/article/Glen-Rice-Jr-Demonstrates-Theres-More-Than-One-Path-to-the-NBA-4165/|title=Glen Rice Jr Demonstrates There's More Than One Path to the NBA|accessdate=2013-05-06|date=2013-05-02|publisher=DraftExpress.com|author=Givony, Jonathan}}</ref> On February 4, Rice posted professional career highs of 35 points and 15 rebounds against [[Springfield Armor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/dleague/games/20130204/RGVSPG/gameinfo.html#nbaGIboxscore|title=Monday, February 4, 2013 7:00 PM ET - MassMutual Center, Springfield, MA|accessdate=2013-02-10|date=2013-02-04|publisher=[[NBA.com]]}}</ref> The day before the [[2013 NBA All-Star Game]], he participated in the 2013 D-League Dream Factory Dunk Contest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/dleague/news/rice_jr_named_pow_2013_03_11.html|title=Rio Grande Valley's Glen Rice Jr. Named NBA D-League Performer of the Week: Rice, Jr. averaged 24.0 points, 11.0 rebounds and 2.3 assists during the week (See Video)|accessdate=2013-03-11|date=2013-03-11|publisher=[[NBA.com]]}}</ref> On March 5, Rice posted 20 points, 14 rebounds and 4 assists against the [[Iowa Energy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/dleague/games/20130305/IWARGV/gameinfo.html#nbaGIboxscore|title=Tuesday, March 5, 2013: 8:00 PM ET - State Farm Arena, Hidalgo, TX|accessdate=2013-03-11|date=2013-03-05|publisher=[[NBA.com]]}}</ref> On March 6, he posted 29 points, 11 rebounds and 3 blocks against the [[Austin Toros]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/dleague/games/20130306/AUSRGV/gameinfo.html#nbaGIboxscore|title=Wednesday, March 6, 2013: 8:00 PM ET - State Farm Arena, Hidalgo, TX|accessdate=2013-03-11|date=2013-03-06|publisher=[[NBA.com]]}}</ref> On March 10, he posted 23 points, 8 rebounds, 3 assists and a steal against the [[Reno Bighorns]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/dleague/games/20130310/RGVRNO/gameinfo.html#nbaGIboxscore|title=Sunday, March 10, 2013: 6:00 PM ET - Reno Events Center, Reno, NV|accessdate=2013-03-11|date=2013-03-10|publisher=[[NBA.com]]}}</ref> On March 11, Rice was named D-League Player of the Week after averaging 24.0 points, 11.0 rebounds, and 2.3 assists in three victories that week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/dleague/news/rice_jr_named_pow_2013_03_11.html|title=Rio Grande Valley's Glen Rice Jr. Named NBA D-League Performer of the Week: Rice, Jr. averaged 24.0 points, 11.0 rebounds and 2.3 assists during the week.|accessdate=2013-03-11|date=2013-03-11|publisher=[[NBA.com]]}}</ref> Following the regular season, Rice was named 2012-13 NBA D-League All-Rookie second team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/dleague/news/nba_development_league_announces_all_nbadleague_selections_2013_04_26.html|title=NBA Development League Announces 2012-13 All-NBA D-League Selections: 17 GATORADE Call-Ups, 11 Players on NBA Rosters Highlight All-NBA D-League Selections|accessdate=2013-04-28|date=2013-04-26|publisher=[[NBA.com]]}}</ref> Rice emerged as a starter and helped the Vipers win their final 16 consecutive games, including three consecutive D-League playoff series sweeps on the way the 2013 NBA D-League championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/default/article/Rio-Grande-Valley-poised-for-2nd-D-League-title-4468410.php|title=Rio Grande Valley poised for 2nd D-League title|accessdate=2013-04-28|date=2013-04-27|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/dleague/games/20130427/SCWRGV/gameinfo.html|title=Warriors Fall to Rio Grande Vipers in NBA D-League Finals|accessdate=2013-04-28|date=2013-04-27|publisher=[[NBA.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/sports/local/article_8acebcee-afb2-11e2-b59a-001a4bcf6878.html|title=RGV Capsules: Vipers notch second title in four years|accessdate=2013-04-28|date=2013-04-27|work=[[The Brownsville Herald]]|author=Silva, Dennis II}}</ref> Rice averaged 25 points, 9.5 rebounds, 4.3 assists, 2 blocks and 2 steals in the playoffs including averaging 29 points, 11.5 rebounds, 4 assists, 3 steals and 3.5 blocks in the D-League finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/dleague/playerfile/glen_rice_jr/|title=Glen Rice #24 Guard|accessdate=2013-04-28|publisher=[[NBA.com]]}}</ref>

===2013 NBA Draft===
As the D-League season wound down, Rice emerged as a sleeper draft choice for the [[2013 NBA Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1593835-the-7-best-2013-nba-draft-prospects-nobody-is-talking-about/page/4|title=The 7 Best 2013 NBA Draft Prospects Nobody Talks About|accessdate=2013-04-07|date=2013-04-05|publisher=[[Bleacher Report]]|author=Wasserman, Jonathan}}</ref> His performances ended up helping him go from the possibility of being undrafted to being taken as early as the late first round. He was one of 60 players invited to the NBA Draft Combine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://probasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2013/05/13/complete-nba-draft-combine-invite-list/|title=Complete NBA Draft Combine invite list|accessdate=2013-05-14|date=2013-05-02|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|author=Helin, Kurt}}</ref> On June 27, 2013, Rice was selected with the 35th overall pick of the NBA Draft by the Philadelphia 76ers, but was traded to the Washington Wizards for the 38th and 54th selections, which turned out to be [[Nate Wolters]] and [[Arsalan Kazemi]], repectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://probasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2013/06/28/wizards-draft-georgetowns-porter-at-least-we-got-that-right/|title=Wizards draft Georgetown<U+2019>s Porter. At least we got that right|accessdate=June 29, 2013|date=June 28, 2013|work=probasketballtalk.nbcsports.com|publisher=NBC Sports|author=bstandig}}</ref> He became the fourth player with D-League experience to be drafted and at 35th overall is the highest D-League veteran to have been drafted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/dleague/glen_rice_jr_becomes_fourth_n_2013_06_28.html|title=Glen Rice Jr. Becomes Fourth NBA D-Leaguer Selected in NBA Draft|accessdate=June 29, 2013|date=June 28, 2013|work=NBA.com|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc.}}</ref>

===Washington Wizards===
Rice signed with the Wizards on July 8.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Monday-s-Sports-Transactions-4652829.php|title=Monday's Sports Transactions|accessdate=2013-07-09|date=2013-07-08|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]}}</ref>

==Personal==
Rice is the son of [[Glen Rice|Glen Rice, Sr.]] and Tracey Starwood.<ref name=4GRJ/>  Glen Rice Sr was the all-time leading scorer for Michigan who led the [[1988<U+2013>89 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|1988<U+2013>89 Wolverines]] to the [[1989 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|National Championship]], and played 15 seasons in the NBA, where was a member of the [[1999<U+2013>2000 Los Angeles Lakers season|1999<U+2013>2000 Los Angeles Lakers championship team]].<ref name=GRJsf3g/> Rice, Jr. has a younger brother G'mitri Rice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gastongazette.com/sports/south-41607-point-aaron.html|title=Prep notebook: South Point has another tie to Shrine Bowl|date=2009-12-16|accessdate=2011-11-26|work=[[Gaston Gazette]]|author=Gardner, Phillip}}</ref>

